<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06032n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06032n">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06032n"> 32(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ O Ferguson ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Sir Samuel Ferguson&rsquo; Moreover, another Belfast friend and mentor, Dr. Robert Gordon, was keeping him up to his highest poetical self by a series of memorable letters, extracts from which Lady Ferguson gives in her Biography of Sir Samuel, as thus: &ldquo;You rejoice me, I speak seriously, by saying you are &lsquo;doing&rsquo;. To be and to do. <mark>O Ferguson</mark>, these little words contain the sum of all man&apos;s destiny. You are strong, and I would have you strike some stroke that will reverberate down the vista of time. Will you, Ferguson?&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS2"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) 41</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
